<validity_requirements>
For an XXE claim to be VALID, you must independently verify:

1. ENTITY EXPANSION
   - External entities are processed by the parser
   - NOT: XML accepted but entities ignored
   - Check: Does entity reference return file content or trigger OAST?

2. FILE OR NETWORK ACCESS
   - Can read local files or make network requests
   - NOT: Just XML parsing without side effects
   - Check: /etc/passwd content or OAST callback?

3. SERVER-SIDE PARSING
   - XML is parsed on the SERVER
   - NOT: Client-side XML parsing (browser)
   - Check: OAST callback from server IP?
</validity_requirements>

<independent_control_tests>
YOU MUST DESIGN YOUR OWN TESTS. Do not reproduce the reporter's tests.

TEST 1: ENTITY EXPANSION TEST
Purpose: Verify external entities are processed
Steps:
1. Submit XXE payload:
   <!DOCTYPE test [<!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///etc/passwd">]>
   <root>&xxe;</root>
2. Check response for /etc/passwd content
3. For blind: Use OAST URL instead of file://

TEST 2: PARSER CONFIGURATION TEST
Purpose: Verify parser allows external entities
Steps:
1. Test different entity types: SYSTEM, PUBLIC
2. Try parameter entities for blind XXE
3. Check error messages for parser hints
</independent_control_tests>

<validity_decision_matrix>
| Entity Reference | Response Content | OAST Callback | Decision |
|-----------------|------------------|---------------|----------|
| &xxe; | File content | N/A | VULNERABLE |
| &xxe; | Error | Yes (from server) | VULNERABLE (blind) |
| &xxe; | Entity literally | No | NOT VULNERABLE |
| &xxe; | Empty/ignored | No | NOT VULNERABLE |
</validity_decision_matrix>

<common_false_positive_patterns>
REJECT if you observe:
- Entity references returned literally (not expanded)
- Parser errors without file content
- DTD processing explicitly disabled
- Client-side XML parsing only
- OAST callback from your browser, not server
</common_false_positive_patterns>
</xxe_verification>
